<solution><div><h3>Worked Solution:</h3>
<p>1. To write <m>z</m> in polar form, we need to find its modulus and argument.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle r = |z| = \sqrt{{}{3}{}^2 + {}{5}{}^2}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle  = \sqrt{{34}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle  = {\sqrt{34}}</m>.</p>
<p>To find the argument, we find the argument of <m>\displaystyle {3} + {5}\cdot i</m>, which is</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle \tan^{-1} \left( \frac{{5}}{{3}} \right) = {1.03}</m></p>
<p>If not in the first quadrant, we need to use the symmetry in the Argand Diagram to find the actual argument, which happens to be <m>\displaystyle {\frac{103}{100}}</m> .</p>
<p>Therefore, the polar form of <m>z</m> is <m> \displaystyle {\sqrt{34}\cdot \left(\mathrm{i}\cdot \sin \left( \frac{103}{100} \right)+\cos \left( \frac{103}{100} \right)\right)}</m> or <m> \displaystyle {\sqrt{34}\cdot \left(0.86\cdot \mathrm{i}+0.51\right)}</m></p>

<p>2. To write <m>z</m> in exponential form, we need to find its modulus and argument.</p>
<p>From the previous part we know that <m>\displaystyle r = |z| = {\sqrt{34}}</m> and <m>\theta = {\frac{103}{100}}</m>.</p>
<p>Therefore, the exponential form of <m>z</m> is <m>\displaystyle {\sqrt{34}\cdot e^{\frac{103\cdot \mathrm{i}}{100}}}</m></p></div></solution>
<answer><p><m>\sqrt{34}\cdot \left(\mathrm{i}\cdot \sin \left( \frac{103}{100} \right)+\cos \left( \frac{103}{100} \right)\right)</m></p></answer>
<answer><p><m>\sqrt{34}\cdot e^{\frac{103\cdot \mathrm{i}}{100}}</m></p></answer>
